<div align="center"><table width="80%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
<tr><td>
<a name="Identification">
<b>Identification</b></td></tr><tr><td>
Extracted from: Coelho, B. W. T., 2004. A review of the bee genus Augochlorella (Hymenoptera: Halictidae: Augochlorini). Systematic Entomology, Vol. 29. 282-323. 
<p> 
Female. Size. (1) Total body length 6–8 mm; (2) forewing 
length 4–5 mm. Structure. (3) Head wider than long, head 
length to width ratio1.07–1.10; (4) elevation of labrum with 
apex orbicular, protuberant and diameter about 1/3 of 
upper margin length of labrum; (5) F10 about 2.5 length 
of F1; (6) preoccipital ridge carinate; (7) pronotal lateral 
angle obtuse, anterolateral margin in dorsal view gently 
concave; (8) anterior mesoscutal border rounded; (9) basal 
area of propodeum about 1.5 longer than metanotum; 
(10) basal area of propodeum crescentic-shaped in outline 
from dorsal view; (11) posterior margin of basal area of 
propodeum distinct, posterolateral regions delimited by 
slight depression; (12) length and width of posterior surface 
of propodeum approximately equal; (13) tegula oval, 1.6 
length to width ratio. Sculpture. (14) Upper paraocular area 
closely punctate, becoming slightly sparsely punctured in 
lower paraocular area, weakly roughened beside antennal 
sockets; (15) supraclypeal area impunctate or very sparsely 
punctate medially, becoming more densely punctured laterally in lower half, surface smooth; (16) clypeus area with 
punctures irregular in size and spacing, smaller and closer at 
margins of clypeus than centrally, distal third of clypeus 
with several somewhat elongate, coarse puctures separated 
by smooth ground; (17) mesoscutum with contiguous punctures, very slightly separated in central area (i ¼ d), and with 
scattered larger hair bases well separated by finely punctured areas, anterior third of scutum finely tranversely 
strigose; (18) scutellum with close punctures (i ¼ d), finer 
than those of mesoscutum, and larger hair bases more concentrated on half posterior, rough surface near posterior 
margin; (19) tegula without conspicuous punctures, surface 
minutely reticulate; (20) pre-episternum coarsely rugosepunctate; (21) mesepisternum more finely rugose-punctate 
than pre-episternum, punctures irregular in size and spacing, smaller and closer in upper part than lower part (i¼ 1–2d), 
surface between punctures irregularly roughened; (22) basal 
area of propodeum with about 35 carinae slightly irregular 
medially, straight laterally, extending full length of basal 
area, ocasionally very small minutely roughened or microreticulate region between ends of median carinae and edge 
of basal area; (23) posterior surface of propodeum finely 
and uniformly microstriated with scattered large hair bases; 
(24) lateral surface of propodeum similar to posterior surface; (25) anterior surface of T1 with minute, unequally 
spaced punctures and with scattered coarser hair bases, ground between punctures faintly lineolate; (26) dorsal surface of T1 finely, weakly and sparsely punctate (d ¼ 3–4d) in 
central area of dull, finely transversely lineolate ground, 
depressed marginal area weak with narrow smooth band 
along edge. Colour. Bright green or blue-green, except: (27) 
mandible dark brown to blackish with reddish apex; (28) 
about apical third of clypeus blackish to dark brown; (29) 
antenna blackish to dark brown, flagellum slightly lighter 
below than above; (30) legs usually dark brown, coxae with 
metallic blue-green highlights; (31) sterna blackish to dark 
brown; (32) posterior marginal zonas and sometimes discs 
of T1 and T2 blackish or brown. Pubescence. (33) Dorsal 
surface with very short, fine, highly plumose light brown to 
whitish hairs; long, simple or branched light brown to whitish hairs on nearly all body parts; apical metasomal areas 
with some black hairs; hairs of outer surfaces of mid and 
hind tibiae whitish or yellowish, dark in some lights. 
<p> 
Male. Size. (1) Total body length 6–8 mm; (2) forewing 
length 4–5 mm. Structure. (3) Head slightly wider than long, 
head length to width ratio 1.02–1.04; (5) antenna reaching 
approximately to scutellum; scape short, not reaching 
median ocellus; F1 1.4–1.5 as wide as long and longer 
than F2; F2 twice as wide as long; F3 longer than F2, 
approximately as long as F1; F4 longer than F1; F5 longer 
than F4; F6 about 1.2 length of F5; F7 about 1.2 length 
of F6; F7 approximately equal to F8, F9 and F10, about 
1.6 as long as wide; F11 about 3 length of F1. (34m) 
hind basitarsus flattened ventrally; (35m) surface of hind 
tibia gently convex; (36m) apical margin of S4 transverse 
with small, very shallow median emargination surrounded 
by area of dense hairs; (37m) anal lip of proctiger with 
about 16 short postanal filaments, closely placed and densely setose, lateral filaments slightly longer than median 
ones; (38m) spiculum narrow; (39m) apical margin of S8 
with median process, without apical setae; (40m) apical 
margin of S7 with median process, with 2–8 setae. Genitalia. 
(41m) gonobasal dorsal lobes weakly projecting over gonocoxites; (42m) small membranous parapenial lobes present; 
(43m) basal process of gonostylus present, without setae; 
(44m) inner lobe of ventral gonostylus with projection 
divided, double margins of about same heights bearing 
row of approximately 30 flattened and elongated setae; 
(45m) outer lobe of ventral gonostylus with about 6 setae 
shorter and finer than those of inner ventral lobe; (46m) 
dorsal process of gonostylus sclerotized, lobe divided into 
two projections, superior projection longer than basal one, 
and with slightly inner side expansion; (47m) penis valve 
moderately expanded laterally, median dorsal ridge bordering depression on inner side; (48m) volsella with triangular 
basal area longer than apical. Sculpture. (14) Lower parocular area with distinctly coarser punctures than those of 
upper area and slightly more spaced apart; (15) supraclypeal area with puctures separated by 1–2 puncture widths 
medially in the lower half; (16) clypeus with punctures 
separated by 1–2 puncture widths; (17) mesoscutum with 
punctures separated by 1–2 puncture widths in central area, 
between parapsidal lines and forwards along median line, and by one puncture width or less elsewhere, surface 
between punctures smooth; (18) scutellum with puctures 
separated by 1–2 puncture widths or less, surface smooth; 
(23) posterior surface of propodeum with fine punctures 
separated by 2–3 puncture widths and scattered large hair 
bases, surface between punctures smooth; (24) lateral surface of propodeum with distinct punctures, separated by 
one puncture width or less, surface finely roughened; (25) 
anterior surface of T1 with scattered hair bases. (26) dorsal 
surface of T1 finely, weakly and sparsely punctate (d¼ 2–3d) 
in central area. Colour. (28) Apical third of clypeus with 
creamy-white tranverse band; (49m) labrum creamy; (29) 
antenna blackish to dark brown, flagellum much lighter 
below than above, sometimes F1, F10 and F11 all dark; 
(30) legs blackish to dark brown, coxae, trochanters and 
femora with metallic blue-green highlights; (31) metasomal 
terga blackish to dark brown with metallic blue-green highlights, especially laterally. Pubescence. (50m) Head and scape, 
densely pubescence; (51m) hind femur without hair tuft; (52m) 
hairs on under surface of hind tibia much shorter than tibial 
diameter; (53m) hind basitarsius with hairs of uniform length 
and density on lower surface from base to apex, about as long 
as width of segment. 
<p> 
Distribution. Northern Bahia (Brazil) to southern Buenos 
Aires (Argentina), westwards to the Andes Cordillera (Fig. 16). 
</td></tr><tr><td><br></td></tr>
